Armed fighting: The MP3 Player against the mobile.
We advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile plays MP3 files, no MP3 player can make calls.
It seems clear that it is better to buy only the phone.
Yet there are sufficient reasons for man to acquire only the reproducer.
The choice depends practically on the way of its use and the requirement of the future owner.
It will probably be difficult for him to acquire the most modern record player to listen to Maxim Turbulenc's latest album on it.
On the other hand, this type of music products such as LP records no longer come out, and as far as their quality is concerned, there is not a single objective reason to continue buying them.
If vinyl records with art rock, jazz or blues music get stuck in your shelves, you’re probably dreaming of at least this type of record player.
This is the same with music on the way, that is, compressed, simplified music - music in MP3.
And here there are categories of price and quality.
For some it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, the same as for a Pink Floyd lover who will hardly taste the market helmets of twenty crowns.
Two ends, between which there is enough space for each.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life
Some of the best players get much more than just playing music and even what not even most mobiles.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
Faced with the most elementary functions such as calling, sending messages, you can play music and video, record both, have a better or worse camera and can even manage to navigate.
And when we take into account the Smartphone and the PDAs will also have in their pocket a small computer.
This is a small miracle as no refrigerator knows how to grill and no TV can photograph.
The universality of mobile phones also brings us disadvantages.
The more functions you use on your mobile, the sooner the display indicator will be lit asking to be recharged.
And music playback is one of the biggest rushes of energy.
Few are mobile devices that play music for more than ten or twelve hours, most much less.
In this sense, music players (especially the simplest) clearly have a higher performance.
Therefore, keep in mind that cheap mobile phones will not play for more than two hours.
If, in addition to this, they constantly call themselves still, for more security, a charger for the work - this also applies to the most expensive appliances.
With the MP3 player you will not have this problem, because even the worst can withstand at least 9 hours of uninterrupted operation after a charge.
Another problem happens when recording music on the mobile.
Unfortunately, only a part of the devices has the universal USB connector and, moreover, not all of them can be connected directly to the computer without special software.
Of course, it is possible to record music directly to the memory card but only in some readers without reduction can the small memory cards that are used in mobile phones be connected.
In players, with some exceptions (iPod), no special software is required.
Simply fill the device with music via the computer's USB.
Most mobiles and players create their own order in the music library according to the name of the performer, album title, genre or also according to user rating.
Some devices only show a directory with tree structure similar to a Windows Finder and some recognize both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
The player tries to serve, the mobile knows more
For the choice of a specific equipmentinterest in the strength of the accumulator, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the convenience of its handling.
If you listen, above all, to music as a background and you will listen to it every day only for a while, as in the tram, then it is enough with any mobile that you play.
This is something that virtually any mobile can achieve.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or player plays the music.
The MP3 is played by everyone and virtually all the music you get will be in this format.
It is among the most widely used and with the exception of it the absolute majority of devices play music in WMA format.
The fewest include the AAC format (the format used by Apple and its iPod).
The best mobile phones also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
Simply visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and purchase a song or album via the mobile internet.
This service could be by itself a weighty argument for acquiring a mobile for music.
Unfortunately, the operators’ offer is miserable and most are limited only to the fleeting success topics of the radios.
The prices are not the lowest either.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (whether by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always carry a mobile phone.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you will find your mobile in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends on whether you always carry headphones or, at least, hands-free.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has virtually every mobile even if it is at least one MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many of the mobiles with music will be its price.
The cheapest ones usually cost less than three thousand.
Between three and four thousand crowns can already acquire a good walkman.
Most of you will be limited by the absence of a classic headphone jack.
The best, even in terms of the technical part, such as phones equipped with a 3.5 mm input. for classic headphones, cost up to fifteen thousand.
Again, the advantage of the players is nothing more than their easy service.
The simplest players - by no means necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - are really handled by anyone.
The minimum functions, their handling similar to the previous current cassettes or also to the disc players is obvious.
It does not pose a threat in the sense that we mistakenly connect to the internet with the mobile and, consequently, gigantic data download account.
What type of device to use
Even the cheapest mobile phones (for example, the Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for changing the memory card (type M2, micro SD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of a suitable card will reach two thousand crowns.
However, be careful.
The basic models are usually equipped with only one card of 2 GB of maximum capacity.
Only the most expensive ones have an 8GB memory.
If you already have a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a look at Cowon, Creativ, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or Iriver.
Depending on the capacity (maximum 2 GB) it is not necessary to spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are considered among the most demanding music lovers take a look at the most specialized mobile-walkman (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices have separate keys for the MP3 which makes a service as comfortable as that of a single player.
The most specialized of all is Sony Ericsson, whose walkman line phones have almost identical use as that of an independent MP3 player.
The same service and the same category in terms of price, about four thousand crowns, but with a higher memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery (usually 15 hours, with a maximum performance of up to 35 hours), the aforementioned brand brings MP3 players.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long before it arrives.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
Following the European Commission’s latest steps in the field of roaming fees regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise – for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS that they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send it from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that really wants to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
The President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, also said that there is no longer room in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with its own network it no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market that brought a significant drop in prices, to which classical operators had to react as well.
At the same time, even before sharks like Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for this type of operators and that they can be successful.
There is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we inform you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
After only half a year, this operator managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, after Mobilking is the Penta group that, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to work effectively, they need much fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not involve relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, these types of virtual operators are usually profiled with low costs – they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that, however, are often countered by the offer of more tight services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a nothing trivial target group can also be a good blow.
This operator is specifically addressed to man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator you like and can be trusted,” says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could hook up in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators rely.
In addition, from the point of view of the service offer is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic it will not be Mobilking.
“We’re talking about expanding this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it doesn’t seem too hopeful.
Rather, it is Mobilking’s launch in other countries in our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for the financial group Penta, told mobil.cz.
Indirectly, he said that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator is already shown by the GTS Novera group that would like to take a step further to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in this, in order to be able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have managed to advance in the meetings," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they flash better times.
It seems that, according to unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now its appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
“At the moment we believe the situation is ideal for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
Until now no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project in this field," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesman for Telefónica O2, told mobil.cz.
The specificity of the Czech market refers to other operators.
T-mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2’s opinion, adds: “To date, we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally profitable, can continue to develop.”
“It will be difficult to find any virtual operator on T-Mobile’s network by the end of the year.
At this point we should already have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied in such a short period of time."
Vodafone focuses its attention on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: “We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost sharing and infrastructure.
We see it as the biggest contribution from the point of view of customers.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field is to partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast mobile internet.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a fall in prices and thus a fall in profits.
So why facilitate entry into competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of this is the grip when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by the public information available on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds: “Furthermore, the competitive environment in the mobile market was not long ago open to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean great demands for him and, above all, for his services."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Licensing (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, she expressed her typical stance on this issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement was concluded on the lease of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of potential stakeholders rather was not interesting enough for classical operators,” added Kristian Chalupa, of the Department of Foreign Relations of the OHSA.
These statements do not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers, this is more than a consideration, apart from that they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile services"
Clearly, pressure on the proper functioning of the market means and the fall in prices do not fall within the interest of the OHIM.
What is really dramatically shocking in this case is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence, offers itself.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in gas stations because it is clear that it is the work of chance and of a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding increase in responsibility in their market performance.
The tools needed to open the mobile market to virtual operators, rather, are lacking, as well as telecommunications regulators," Chalupa added in his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is clearly a relevant market analysis by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> that telecommunications are, from the point of view of commercial tendering, a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech traders has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile operator – with all its logic – has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument were not accepted, at least for OHIM it should be a warning that three mobile operators are strikingly rising in a similar fashion.
The current complaints from stakeholders (including the aforementioned company GTS Novera) show that in all negotiations with the operators there are many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility in the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have met with him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law was recently introduced to expand the competition of the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> in the field of commercial tenders that was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
This should be well known to UOHS representatives, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one's looking
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator is still working unnoticed that a few already exist in Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile services.
Usually only a few elected ones get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases like the ones cited were discovered, one could speak of a breach of contract conditions that could result in the end of collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrová replied to the question on this issue.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach responsible people.
Precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators oppose this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make nothing depreciable profits and, at the same time – unlike authentic virtual traders – they in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so much percent of customers.
These, furthermore, must accept that their phone’s SIM card is not in their name so they cannot absolutely dispose of it as a normal customer of the carriers.”
Precisely this is what should seem to the <0xC4><0x8C>TU minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators surround the eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the UOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activities and if it does not want to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive?
As was already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in prices for services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classic operators tried to more or less protect themselves from this intrusion.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market eventually too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the more advanced countries, however, regulators have now intervened and in none of the cases defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to make the first virtual operator emerge and with him began to emerge others.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body passes this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience, we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of attributions in these cases suits them.
But let us not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator really gets to these lands, then the Czech mobile market is probably starting to move again.
If one of the operators lets in a mobile virtual operator, it will be difficult for the OHIM to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
