Rats also have feelings.
It is said that a rat or a cockroach feeling the danger escapes, why is he also afraid?
Joseph Le Doux, the scientist in the field of neurology, is convinced that many animals also have feelings.
How can it be controlled if they, behaving in the manner similar to us, feel the same?
An internet magazine called "Edge" has been publishing the contributions of famous scientists for many years.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series the chosen answers to the question: What do you think is true without being able to prove it?
I think animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it until now, although we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case we can at least expect it because all human brains have the same fundamental configuration.
But as soon as we dedicate ourselves to other species and include questions about sensation and consciousness in general, we enter the unknown realm because the hardware does not match.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same as the other animals: it becomes dead, flees or attacks.
People behave similarly, from which some scientists draw conclusions about comparable subjective experience.
Of course I won't believe it.
Two aspects of the brain structure make it difficult to infect our subjective experience with that of animals.
First, they almost always include the circuits associated by human consciousness of the lateral prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex (due to their participation in short memory and conduct-directing executive functions).
This broad part is much more developed in the case of humans than that of other primates and seems to be absolutely missing in other creatures.
Considering at least the aspects pertaining to our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal lobe of the cerebral cortex, including knowledge about who we are and the ability to plan and decide, there is a reason to assume that even man differs from other primates.
Another peculiarity lies in the linguistic nature of man: Since most of his experience is linked to language, it often means that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals can be excluded.
But even though consciousness would not depend on language, it would influence it so that animal consciousness, created as it were, would in many cases differ from most of our states of consciousness.
