The back door of the CBGB, the punk rock monument that closed in 2006, opened at Extra Place, but the street is perhaps best known for the photograph of the establishment coming out on the cover of Ramones' album "Rocket to Russia".
"The setting was magnificent," said Danny Fields, the Ramones' manager, who took the photograph in November 1976.
"It was full of garbage, pieces of clothing and pieces of barrels, posters, sheets, ropes."
Some residents, including bloggers writing about the East Village burgeoning, have opposed the idea of selling Extra Place, arguing that public goods, however modest, should remain public.
Others have praised Extra Place as a rare piece, virtually unchanged, a ray of the city that should be guarded.
Jeremiah Moss, who runs a blog called Jeremiah's Vanishing New York (subtitled, "The Book of Lamentations: A Bitterly Nostalgic Look at a City in the Process of Going Extinct"), has made available part of a talk in the city's history about Extra Place, published by The New Yorker in 1952.
The author, Brendan Gill, wrote: "Extra Place is a somewhat narrow and dead-end alley, dark also by day and marked by rusted iron warehouse doors and counter-windows, with weeks-old newspapers blown along the canals."
With few exceptions, the street looked more or less the same on a recent afternoon.
A rat was cured through the back of the street and stood near the door that was used to enter the CBGB and which now houses a luxury clothing store.
Graffiti on the walls and a 22-oz empty beer bottle were near a new batch of discarded newspapers.
Some interns said they rarely paid attention to Extra Place, but suggested that it might be given a cleanup.
Mr. Fields, for his part, noted that some people underestimate the attractive power of the street in its current state.
