Calling Hispanic voters effectively is a difficult business.
The education proposals made by Barack Obama are an example of this.
Mr. Obama’s campaign notes that “African Americans and Latino students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” and this is a very certain consideration.
To combat such differences in learning outcomes, Obama’s education plan specifically advocates, among other things, “bilingual transitional education” for English-students.
However, the question open to Mr. Obama is whether the commitment of bilingual education, which prefers classroom instruction in languages other than English, will be effective in nullifying the distance in the final results.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, an officially recognized elementary school in the eastern Los Angeles County region.
In this school the vast majority of students are Hispanics and low-income families:
More than a third of students, many of whom are newly arrived, are learning English.
However, an incredible 100 percent of fourth-year students have been positively evaluated in the 2008 math exam.
and almost equally astounding 93 percent have mastered the English language and arts test.
This incredible success has been achieved using a different ingredient than Mr. Obama favored.
Sixth Street School emphasizes review and practice, constant assessment of competencies, and does not tolerate any apology attitude.
In addition, and this is where Mr. Obama should take note, according to Linda Mikels, the principal on Sixth Street, the school’s approach to teaching English to students is in “total immersion.”
Immersion in English means the almost exclusive use of the language in the treatment of the contents of the instruction.
Mrs. Mikels, who opposes bilingual education, told me, “We’ve had extraordinary successes with students like the latter who have arrived from Mexico and that if you enter the classroom 12 months later you wouldn’t be able to pick up what was.”
