Will Mr. Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model to replicate by other schools with large populations of Hispanic-English students?
The results achieved by this school should remove any doubt about the answer, but the idea of his party’s politicians on the issue of education (the Associations for National Education have long been advocates of bilingual education) and their very constant support for bilingual education obscures the prediction of Mr. Obama’s response.
While it is true that immigrants should learn English, Mr. Obama has recently trivialized the issue by letting people stop worrying about legislation that is only written in English.
and instead, he said, "you should make sure your child can speak Spanish."
If Mr. Obama really wants to improve the system and close gaps, he should carefully consider models of education that work well, rather than despise or trivialize them.
