Boys for home delivery continue to make their metal tea carts resonate through the sidewalks and bring muffin trays for breakfast meetings.
Latino men continue to crawl between busy apartment buildings, like human mules, with 50 eccentric stamping shirts hanging to a yoke across their shoulders. Office workers still wait in line for their meals to take in the morning, and it is still impossible to catch a taxi between 4am and 7pm on working days.
Employees are still waiting to queue for their bagel at the vendor’s carts, and it is still impossible to find a taxi between four and five in the afternoon on weekdays.
It seemed to me that there was no crisis at all, until this Thursday afternoon, with all the pessimistic forecasts there are, I decided to open a new savings account.
Although I had calculated the time needed for the operation to coincide with the calm of the late afternoon at my local JP Morgan Chase subsidiary, a queue of about 20 people was already waiting.
And not in front of the employee’s window, to withdraw your cash or make a deposit, but in front of the customer service bank, where lifelong customers order their checkbooks, tourists look for instructions to go to Macy’s large warehouses and new customers want to open their accounts.
Most of these people preceded me, I was later informed by Starr, my “trusted personal banker,” and they were in line for the same reason as me.
Unlike me, they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks in places where they had switched, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Staten Island.
They had taken their money from the so-called savings associations (a bit like a construction society), from the credit unions and the savings boxes of their hometown whose branches only function within the state of belonging, and who say they treat customers as their family.
Over the past year, 15 of these banks have silently failed.
In recent days, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers headed home Friday night for the weekend, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in savings deposits, was looking for a bailout buyer.
Workers in offices and shops standing in front of me, fearing another collapse, were transferring their money to a bank to what is considered a safe haven, which is what most Wall Street bailouts are doing.
Ordinary New Yorkers have become financial experts in recent weeks.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket, speaking on the phone, was referring to Lehman Brothers, the failed bank, and its afflicted-looking CEO, Dick Fuld, commented on the matter with familiarity as if they were complaining about a colleague’s inactivity.
