Speaking Sleepy
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean these people who wake up very upset telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while they’re asleep.
The first time it happens at best you take a scare, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquies.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (peeing asleep) or somnambulism, but it doesn’t have to be so.
As we have already mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever rates, stressful situations or overexcitation.
However, it is an unstudied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that he speaks in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a whisper or the opposite (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him a way out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, so it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress picture).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to bed.
So look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a bit violent.
With children very nervous and difficult to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will help the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
Once the sleep talks appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even if he’s talking, he’s sleeping and therefore he’s resting.
Remember that if you are very anxious during several episodes you should consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he is saying (which is not the most common), don’t be tempted to interrogate him to get him information.
You won’t get anything, because when you’re asleep you’re not conscious enough to organize your thought.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, with which you are very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can interrogate him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
This leads to children's anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s nothing bad, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
