Interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again become one of the safest and most effective blood providers in the world.
And above all, it regained public confidence that had been seriously vacillated by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
National blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated with Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public discontent, the Government of Canada conducted a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, to clarify the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and make recommendations for such a disaster not to be repeated.
While Judge Krever was delayed in presenting his relationship, certain provinces then created a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the reports by Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, nearly 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Decary recalls.
The situation was disheartening.
After having made a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” he says before proudly asserting that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation, on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we witnessed in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, Decary says.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the reports by Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious disease can arise from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been undoubtedly shown that this disease is transmitted through the blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique of HIV detection appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until now were based.
The nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than a week.
This substantially reduces the risk that certain donors will be infected without our knowledge and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS from a blood transfusion.
Today, one person in 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
“That means you’ll have to distribute 12 million blood products before someone gets infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I believe that it is possible today to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to regain health without worries,” says the head of Héma-Québec’s management.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
You have to be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary says before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for a sufficient supply.
" Needs are increasing as the population ages.
Because anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average regroups only 3 per cent of eligible Quebecers for blood donation. "
All people in good health, aged 18 and who meet the eligibility criteria can, however, donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they traveled to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today’s life is very unbridled, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating your blood,” says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is filled with a blood-rich stem cell that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
"We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bench our thousandth blood sample from the umbilical cord and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We should start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
“Many moms are disappointed that they can’t enjoy this,” as Héma-Québec doesn’t have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
