Free Opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Following an Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the largest gold company in the world attempted a defamation trial of six million euros against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a "transparent public debate".
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of persecution for defamation, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, the best way to hold a public debate would be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the nearly bottomless pockets of the miner.
The tactic, in these uneven struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly arrangement that will dampen the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it was before public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by garrotting.
It was therefore sufficient for the miner to open her books, her records and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the funding of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects petitions and letters of support for the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a "public" debate disregarding the views of the latter?
According to the Vice-President, it seems that this word refers only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In a democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What Barrick Gold doesn’t understand — or what he doesn’t want to understand — is that the audience that supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does it mainly because they reject the brutal way of mining.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but based on civilized changes of arguments, and not on what many people perceive as a persecution-bite (persecuting the "public debate," Barrick Gold has just filed a demand with respect to the authors of Noir Canada urging them not to use this word anymore).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on the freedom of university search and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and make a debate about facts and interpretations, which are the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the rich businesses of this world in a country like Canada, under the penalty of many persecutions, who can do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific norms used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s excessive persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he does not want to make a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
