Very soon, on October 8, the criminal trial against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing fraud of significant harm, in business mode, continuously and in an organized way in addition to other crimes, including the falsification of documents.
According to the Prosecutor's Office, they used the funds obtained in the public tenders for their own purposes, often justifying the fulfillment of tasks with false invoices.
The public and municipal funds - in their entirety about HUF 65 million - were partly in the treasury of the organization Fiatal Baloldal and partly in the pocket of private persons.
The method, which was disclosed by the researchers also, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public tenders with false invoices behind which there was no real execution, the various associations never fulfilled their assumed obligations.
According to the prosecution, most of the invoices were false.
For this purpose they obtained the talonaries in the market of the District of Józsefváros and the circular stamps were made in the city of Kiskunhalas.
And the question of which company to make the counterfeit invoice was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Lados.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and these served as a model for making the invoices that they submitted, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labor, as well as in the City of the Capital.
These invoices were mostly signed by István Lados and his accomplice András <0xC5><0x90>ri, who according to our information rather wrote the necessary reports to obtain the public subsidies.
During one of his "study trips" Lados chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the manager of the center - so many people do not fit at once in that place.
Similarly, the invoice issued in the summer of 2002 for the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation - later called Együtt to Armadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
For a hostel in the town of Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, yet on the bill there were one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of high-fashion invoices also exaggerated when they pointed to the Pigal Kft. gastronomic center because in the holding of books of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents on behalf of Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért and Hoppa.
Gy<0xC5><0x91>z<0xC5><0x91> Farkas, the company’s manager, told hvg.hu that when he was quoted by the prosecutor’s office and shown the invoices, he already knew they were fake documents.
"In the stamp, our company name and NIF appeared in the wrong place."
He added: in addition to the formal problems, he also did not agree that according to the invoice one hundred people were accommodated, since they only have eleven rooms in which not so many people can be accommodated.
In addition, meals were also included in the bill, while the restaurant has not worked for a long time.
The enthusiastic invoice manufacturers were also not informed that the chosen travel agency in Budapest exclusively organizes trips abroad, so in the cash payment invoice they foolishly indicated a trip within Hungary as a service, which also did not coincide with the agency’s practice of issuing invoices.
In addition, as was learned during the investigation, they also included VAT in the document, even though travel outside the territory of the European Union was tax-exempt.
Among other things, the VAT measure was also incorrect in the four documents issued by the Hotel Révfülöp Kft. for the Jobb Jöv<0xC5><0x91>ért Foundation, since the services of such a company are not charged with a 25 but only with 15 per cent VAT, and the hotel employees only extended machine-made invoices although the invoice was manual.
In addition, the "senders" made other mistakes as well, as in the case of a company in which they put on the invoice as an activity carried out road transport to which - it was known during the investigations of the prosecutor's office - does not carry out the company founded as an investment consultant.
Also due to formal differences - improper format of the invoice, false stamp - it was known that the invoices sent for Együtt to Armadik Évezredért Alapítvány, for XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and for Biztos Pont were false.
As in the case of Ravenna Bt. or the Kunfehértó Sports Camp, whose representatives denied having issued those invoices.
The counterfeiters also paid no attention to the fact that when the group of Fiatal Városért Egyesület ate there (2001) the HIB Kft. of Nyíregyháza was in the process of liquidation, so the person in charge of the liquidation process - according to our information - denied having issued such a document.
