Overlapping Psychology: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
New York University neurologists and economists have discovered the neurological-economic foundations of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played the lottery, the other participated in an auction, and in the meantime, the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment were examined using the functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) system.
In both games participants could earn money, but during auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called the stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, along with many other functions, plays a role in the nervous system’s “self-prize” mechanism.
Thus, according to the scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention to not provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To support their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against a person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more prize money.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in the event of losing the auction, the group members would lose even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure.
However, by checking the neurologists' hypothesis, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winning" group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
Until now, auctions have been explained only by the joy of winning and the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped solve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, professor of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should I go to the doctor?
About 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 receive treatment because many of the patients do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms are very similar; they are characteristic of liver infection and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses dependent on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and with body moods (sperm, vagina mood, saliva).
It is advisable for travelers to protect themselves with a vaccine against viruses A and B, there are no vaccines against C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by poor general condition, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After that appear on the skin and on the white of the eyes jaundice, the stool becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people die in the world from cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to calculations, only one in ten infected people receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment, it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most infected people do not know that they are sick because this pathogen gradually destroys the cells of the liver and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Therefore, premature recognition, systematic medical check-up, is very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who wear tattoos.
There are currently about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory checkup as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptoms.
The disease has cure if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the contagion and prevent cancer.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its goal is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and to the importance of their premature recognition.
Does it hurt less those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, the religious faith has a calming effect that also relieved the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed how religious belief influences human pain, the British newspaper The Telegraph reported.
As part of this unique experiment, they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while everyone was looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of a series of researches in which, alongside academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians from different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis took place as follows; they attached a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the 17th-century Virgin Mary, by Sassoferrato, and the 15th-century Lady of the Arminio by Leonardo da Vinci.
The researchers hoped that the spectacle of the Virgin Mary would provoke a certain religious mood among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
Patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during that period while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics said that looking at the Virgin Mary they felt in “security” as “protected” people, “they were reassured and in their heart reigned peace”.
When they looked at the religious theme, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any such impactful image you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
“We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
