On the other hand, skeptics who make a parallel with the Orwelian view do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google’s primary goal is to gather as much personal data as possible about its users, and this is necessary to be able to meet the original goals of Google’s founders: “We gather all the information in the world in one system!”
According to Google’s leader, the company, even after ten years of work that revolutionized the world, is still in the early stages of being able to process all the information.
To the question of what is going to happen in five years Schmidt replied: I would like Google to be able to answer questions like “What to do tomorrow?” or “What would be the job that best suits me?” – however, software will not be able to answer seemingly simple questions as long as there is not enough user information.
Not all Internet users are aware that while browsing the Web they accurately store the searched keywords, IP addresses and pages where they went at the end of the search.
Thanks, for example, to Personalized Search, which debuted two years ago, users can store their own browsing history, they can check again what they were looking for before, what they opened and thanks to this history will generate much more personalized searches - on this same logic will be based the Recommendations, on which the system will offer us products and services based on the previously defined preferences and store.
What will happen if they take advantage of my data against myself, if they collect information about my activities? - ask those users who are concerned by seeing Google's information monopoly.
In most cases rather the potential represented by the company is what can be fearful and not remorse, fear of punishment, longing for freedom or rebellion against power.
However, it is already a confirmed fact that not only retain, but in justifiable cases also cede to third parties all the expressions sought, in these cases there is nothing that protects the personal rights of Internet users.
The most debated example in recent times was perhaps the coordinated action against Brazilian paedophiles, when Google gave the Brazilian government the information from its website, called Orkut, to identify paedophiles.
On the other hand, internet users who care about human rights were relieved in May when the company along with the EFF, an organization for the defense of electronic rights, successfully demonstrated before the court that it was right in its dispute with the FBI: according to the ruling, Google could not be compelled, by any of the points of the F-type constitution, to request information from the FBI.
(At the same time, the federal government managed to get under the pretext of reinforcing the child protection law passed years ago, about fifty thousand web addresses and about a thousand searched phrases, but without getting the search lists of individual users, nor the complete lists of web pages and keywords of the last two months.)
This is the rather contradictory opinion about Google: it is criticized by those who fear to provide their personal data because they think that their privacy, their private life is being harmed by starting to use Google’s services, and rebel against it as against multinational companies of conservative image.
Meanwhile, the American geek culture and its enthusiastic followers, internet users and users from other countries, see in them the future generation, the "avant-garde corporation", not so its rival, Microsoft, cataloged by its Windows as the conqueror of the World, no matter how much they both fight for the same goal.
This can happen because Google unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for their applications, the code is open and the free program package, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it may also be because geeks accurately see the very problematic relationship between human rights and the Internet that was produced just by one of the most mentioned keywords in recent years: the Web 2.0.
