The smart car mimics the flight of the owl
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not imitation of the existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, that of the beetles.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, beetles gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C car robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can avoid all collisions.
During the flight each owl creates its own oval private space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technology director of RP and development and research.
Composite eyes of owls that are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of compound eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the vehicle’s microprocessor which immediately turns into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the vehicle robot mimicking the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels as necessary.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If not, the vehicle's robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered unavoidable.
The whole process should reflect what a hog does to avoid other hogs.
This process should be done in an open and closed eye.
However, unlike the buckets, the movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the bumblebees to avoid other bumblebees, here they only used as a possibility for the robot of the car the rotary movement and the acceleration further the braking.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, meaning they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process the data, let alone the storage.
This apparatus in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few dozen kilobytes of memory.
There is no need for gigabyte or megabyte memory.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which, according to Nissan’s calculations, can be incorporated into mass-produced models within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination, avoiding existing obstacles in their path.
