Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices rose by 0.1 percent compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices, the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices rose by 0.7 percent from the previous month and by 3.2 percent from the previous year.
Industrial selling prices rose only to a minimal extent, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose minimally, by 0.1 percent compared to July.
The largest increase in the magnitude of prices occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear sector (2.8 percent), primarily due to the 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of the plastics and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemicals production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electrical machinery and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
They did not change the prices of papermaking, publishing and printing.
In the rest of the processing industry sectors, prices rose between 0.2 and 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water, which represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in August, primarily due to the effect of the increase in official prices from July 1.
In a comparison of a twelve-month period - in domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the highest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4%).
In the metalworking sector there was an increase of 13.2 percent, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of determining weight, there was an increase of 11 percent.
Prices declined in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machinery and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
During the past year in the processing industry globally, prices rose by 10.2 percent.
Electricity, gas, heat and water prices surpassed previous year’s prices by 18.7 percent.
In the month of August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly increase in prices (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices rose by 0.3 per cent, while prices in the energy and intermediate sectors remained unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
There was a decrease of 6.8 per cent in the consumer goods industry and 1.4 per cent in investment goods.
The industry’s export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 per cent.
The price of our national currency in one month decreased by 1.7 per cent with respect to the euro and by 7.1 per cent with respect to the dollar, compared with August 2007 strengthened by 7.5 per cent with respect to the euro and 15.9 per cent with respect to the dollar.
