"Most young Gypsies have not finished high school and because of the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible part can get a university diploma."
Mr. Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, plays a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economies of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, it is necessary to raise a wide awareness of these issues both among Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the earlier a gypsy student starts school, the more chances he will have to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumption taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be assured of the right to a quality education and ensure the abolition of segregated and low-level education," said Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary to accelerate immediately the processes of school segregation, for this it is of fundamental importance that the correct compliance with the existing and planned anti-discrimination directives.
“We must break the vicious cycle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full-fledged citizens.”
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities, held annually since last year's Berlin meeting, which was held under the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities", is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level of the Member States.
