MP3 Players Under Charge, Put Hearing at Risk
Listening to high-volume music for a long time using portable music devices such as MP3 players can cause permanent damage to hearing.
The European Commission cites the opinion of the EU's newly identified Scientific Commission on Emerging Health Risk (Csserri) in a statement released in Brussels today.
"From this scientific opinion - read the note - it emerges that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music with portable musical devices weekly for more than an hour a day having the device at high volume risk a permanent loss of hearing capacity."
“I am concerned that such a high number of young people who frequently use portable music devices and cell phones at a high acoustic level can unconsciously ruin their ears in an irreparable way,” says Meglena Kuneva.
"A clear risk emerges from the scientific evidence - EU responsibility follows - and we must react quickly.
What counts is to raise consumer awareness and make this information public domain.
We must also examine the existing control systems in the light of this scientific opinion, so that they are widely effective and have the pace with the new technology."
Brussels had asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, seeing the large use of portable musical devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise that that causes.
“Scientists confirm that this is a matter of concern and the European Commission will now examine together with member states and stakeholders what measures could eventually be taken to better protect children and adolescents from noise exposure from portable music devices and related devices.”
At present, there is already a European safety standard limiting the noise level of portable music devices to 100 dB, but concern increases as the hearing damage that can result from excessive exposure to such sources of noise.
It is possible to greatly limit these damages by resorting to solutions such as reducing levels and time of exposure to noise.
In its opinion, the EU Scientific Committee notes that if users of portable music devices listen to loud (more than 89 decibels) music for only 5 hours per week they exceed the currently in force limit for the maximum noise allowed at the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for longer periods risk a permanent loss of hearing after a period of 5 years.
It means it affects 5-10% of users of such devices and the number can be quantified between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
