Farewell to the old Paradiso cinema, the cities cancel the historic halls
The historic cinemas close in favour of the Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively photographs what is happening in the major Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticulous in the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
To disappear are almost always historical places, full of memory," it is as if a friend died, a acquaintance with whom he shared a piece of place and so much excitement", Notes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago always won the cousin Oscar and the grand prize of the jury in Cannes, which told the poetry of a cinema room in such a way that he lived the province and the nostal.
The figures given by the ANEC, the main association of merchants, speak clearly: in the last five years they have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay most are the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are first, Emilia-Romagna with 82 cinemas less, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the cause of its disappearance is the advent of multiplex, these three Italian regions have registered the largest number of new meticulous cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” notes Paolo Protti, president of ANEC, “it would be useful to build new structures but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all of its frequenters are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the previous debt of the state is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful from the ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect the existing laws.
To sustain the sector would need between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that is concerned about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema monkey room both in the historic center and in the periphery.
Among the rules envisaged are tax facilitation measures in favour of managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
“It is an initiative that I like,” Giuseppe Tornatore observes, “and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by setting up other measures.
It is true that to contrast the extra power of meticulous icons, traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a subject that was always important to me: the closure of Bagheria cinema, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make the "New Paradise Cinema", which I had been thinking for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass by the Rialto or Quirinale via Nazionale already closed, where I have lived so many shared emotions, not to see the posters blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.
